1.body: This book is for anyone interested in compiling Rust to android, iOS, and web assembly for fast, reliable code on the mobile. You should know some Rust, and be familiar with Kotlin, Swift, and JavaScript. You don't need to be an expert in any of them.

10.body: We will be developing the core logic for our library. We aim to create a program that works efficiently in Rust and can run on any platform. So, our first step is to make it work in Rust. Let's get started!

2.body: The book is written to be read from start to finish. You should follow along: writing, compiling, and running the tutorial's code yourself.
2.breadcrumbs: Introduction Â» How to read this book?
2.title: How to read this book?

3.body:
Since the book contains every line of code needed for the implementation, the snippets are quite precise. A snippet with all the bells and whistles looks like this: [package]
name = "mobile"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021" [lib]
name = "exa"
crate-type = ["staticlib", "cdylib"] [dependencies] In the center, you have the new code to add or modify. It may have a few faded out lines above and below to show where it goes in the exising surrouding code.
3.title: Snippets

4.body: Rust gives programmers low-level control and reliable performance. It is free from the non-deterministic garbage collection pauses that plague Kotlin/Swift. Programmers have control over indirection, monomorphization, and memory layout.
4.breadcrumbs: Introduction Â» Low-Level Control with High-Level Ergonomics
4.title: Low-Level Control with High-Level Ergonomics

5.body: Existing code bases don't need to be thrown away. You can start by porting your most performance-sensitive Swift/Kotlin functions to Rust to gain immediate benefits. And you can even stop there if you want to. I strongly recommend installing all of your Rust toolchains using rustup. The code of this tutorial is available on Ghamza-Jd/exa-lib This book is open source! Find a typo? Did we overlook something? Is something missing? Send us a Pull Request!
5.breadcrumbs: Introduction Â» Do Not Rewrite Everything
5.title: Do Not Rewrite Everything

6.body: In this section we're going to talk about the architecture of this library
6.title: Architecture

7.body: The heart of our library, it contains code that works independent from the OS and the chip. The core of the library should be like any rust library out there, our twist is porting it to other platforms.
7.title: Core

8.body: Porting our rust library requries us to write glue code, each platform has its set of conventions they follow. Java has JNI (Java Native Interface) and iOS uses C conventions.
8.title: Glue

9.body: So our architecture is making the logic inside of core using rust, and our problem will be only about writing glue code. Now when we want to introduce another platform, the web for an instance, we only have to worry about writing a glue code to support web.
9.title: Core + Glue
